Niemann had arrived in Las Palmas in 1939 after a long career in Morocco. He had 
resided in the African territory since 1907, together with his uncle-by-marriage Carl 
Ficke, a prominent merchant and businessman who had been in Morocco since 1899. 
During the First World War, Ficke and Niemann had been imprisoned in French Africa 
for inciting rebellion to drive the French out of Morocco. 61 Niemann was pardoned, 
and on his return to Germany in November 1916 he offered the German govern-
