Niemann's organization also specialized in sabotage and subversive activities. His 
agents sought not only to attack Allied ships and inland facilities, but also to foment 
riot and rebellion in the Allied territories of North Africa. These subversive activities 
involved infiltration of the French colonies and the systematic delivery of weapons and 
ammunition to local residents. 68 According to Allied intelligence records, the Germans 
attempted to sabotage the SS Hartington while it was anchored at the Port of La Luz for 
repairs between June and July 1942. However, the plan was abandoned in light of the 
Allies' close watch over the ship while it was docked. 69 After the Italian surrender and 
under Allied pressure, the Spanish Government agreed to hand over the Italian ships 
anchored in Spanish ports to the Allies. The KO-Spanien tried to prevent this transfer 
and planned various sabotage actions in Spain. In Las Palmas and Tenerife, the crew 
of the Italian ships, acting either on their own initiative or under pressure from the 
German consulate, tried to destroy the ship's machinery. In addition, José Segura, a 
Spaniard who was part of Gruppe II of the Abwehr in Las Palmas, admitted to having 
placed explosive charges onboard one of the ships. None of these attempted acts of 
sabotage was successful. 70 
